WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:04.510
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:04.510 --> 00:00:19.210
[ Silence ]

00:00:19.210 --> 00:00:20.510
&gt;&gt; All right.

00:00:20.510 --> 00:00:21.810
Welcome, gentleman.

00:00:21.810 --> 00:00:23.110
My name is Todd Harvey,

00:00:23.110 --> 00:00:24.410
I'm a curator at the
American Folk Life Center

00:00:24.410 --> 00:00:25.710
at the Library of Congress.

00:00:25.710 --> 00:00:29.440
I want to thank you for
joining us this afternoon

00:00:29.440 --> 00:00:31.790
after your concert,
after your lunch.

00:00:31.790 --> 00:00:33.870
You're all refreshed.

00:00:33.870 --> 00:00:39.670
I'd first like to introduce John
Cohen and the Down Hill Strugglers

00:00:39.670 --> 00:00:44.270
so that we in the future
know who everyone is.

00:00:44.270 --> 00:00:51.970
This is, from left to right, Eli
Smith; John Cohen in the jacket;

00:00:51.970 --> 00:00:57.880
Jackson Lynch in the white shirt;
and Walker Shephard on the end.

00:00:57.880 --> 00:01:00.080
These are the Down Hill Strugglers.

00:01:00.080 --> 00:01:05.180
Today September 25, 2015.

00:01:05.180 --> 00:01:07.480
And we're here in the
Coolidge Auditorium

00:01:07.480 --> 00:01:10.560
in the lovely Jefferson building.

00:01:10.560 --> 00:01:12.670 position:56%
I want to thank you for the concert.

00:01:12.670 --> 00:01:17.270
I want to thank you for agreeing
to move your concert to today

00:01:17.270 --> 00:01:19.500
to accommodate the Pope's visit.

00:01:19.500 --> 00:01:23.910
John, I understand the Holy
Father himself reached out to you

00:01:23.910 --> 00:01:28.660
to ask you if you would change
the date of your concert.

00:01:28.660 --> 00:01:30.870
He's a big [inaudible]
fan, I know that.

00:01:30.870 --> 00:01:33.000
&gt;&gt; He's from Latin America.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:36.540
&gt;&gt; They didn't want members of
Congress to have to make a choice,

00:01:36.540 --> 00:01:41.030
and so we graciously moved aside.

00:01:41.030 --> 00:01:44.510
And what an amazing
concert you all gave today.

00:01:44.510 --> 00:01:45.810
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:01:45.810 --> 00:01:51.480
&gt;&gt; I just wonder how you found the
acoustics in the room today, Eli?

00:01:51.480 --> 00:01:53.860
&gt;&gt; Yeah. Well, thank you.

00:01:53.860 --> 00:01:55.680
It was a really fun concert.

00:01:55.680 --> 00:01:59.590
And the Coolidge Auditorium
has amazing acoustics.

00:01:59.590 --> 00:02:03.280
It's one of the best places
I've ever played I think.

00:02:03.280 --> 00:02:05.510
&gt;&gt; What about you, Jackson?

00:02:05.510 --> 00:02:08.870
You've got a loud kind
of fiddle style,

00:02:08.870 --> 00:02:13.160
and I wonder if you
could hear yourself.

00:02:13.160 --> 00:02:14.460
&gt;&gt; Oh, yeah.

00:02:14.460 --> 00:02:19.510
I wish I could play in here
with nobody else in here.

00:02:19.510 --> 00:02:20.810
It sounded really good.

00:02:20.810 --> 00:02:22.640
&gt;&gt; Yeah, sorry about that, man.

00:02:22.640 --> 00:02:24.110
&gt;&gt; Sorry, we exist, yeah.

00:02:24.110 --> 00:02:25.540
&gt;&gt; But you're talking
about the audience,

00:02:25.540 --> 00:02:27.870
with the audience being gone?

00:02:27.870 --> 00:02:29.870
&gt;&gt; Oh, I just mean I could
sit in here for hours

00:02:29.870 --> 00:02:35.960
and just play by myself, you know.

00:02:35.960 --> 00:02:40.010
&gt;&gt; What does it compare
to in different halls?

00:02:40.010 --> 00:02:43.840
Well, can you think of any
halls that it compares to?

00:02:43.840 --> 00:02:48.830
&gt;&gt; It kind of sounds like a
dance hall, a big dance hall

00:02:48.830 --> 00:02:58.620
where the room sound travels really
well and everyone can hear it like,

00:02:58.620 --> 00:03:01.700
in the back the same
as in the front.

00:03:01.700 --> 00:03:04.700
&gt;&gt; We've played in
some old halls touring.

00:03:04.700 --> 00:03:06.930
&gt;&gt; And I guess it does in a way,
it reminds me of that a little bit.

00:03:06.930 --> 00:03:09.680
I remember that opera house in
Upstate New York a few years ago.

00:03:09.680 --> 00:03:11.810
&gt;&gt; Yeah. It just has
a big sound like that.

00:03:11.810 --> 00:03:14.230
&gt;&gt; Didn't we play in
a GA [inaudible]

00:03:14.230 --> 00:03:15.950
in Southern Illinois or Ohio?

00:03:15.950 --> 00:03:17.250
&gt;&gt; Yeah, that was in Ohio.

00:03:17.250 --> 00:03:21.240 position:56%
It was something like that, although
this place is much more finely tuned

00:03:21.240 --> 00:03:22.540
than that.

00:03:22.540 --> 00:03:26.870
&gt;&gt; Don't really need a
microphone to play in this room.

00:03:26.870 --> 00:03:28.170
&gt;&gt; No, I didn't think so.

00:03:28.170 --> 00:03:32.090
Yeah, I think you could have
done just fine without it.

00:03:32.090 --> 00:03:35.000 position:56%
&gt;&gt; No, but there's something about
the sound that makes that everything

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:37.670
that you do very present.

00:03:37.670 --> 00:03:44.450
And I was interested that when
we played before the sound test,

00:03:44.450 --> 00:03:48.370
I thought the sound would get
deadened when the audience came.

00:03:48.370 --> 00:03:52.290
But the audience came and the
sound didn't get deadened.

00:03:52.290 --> 00:03:54.510
Maybe the audience got deadened.

00:03:54.510 --> 00:03:57.150
[ Laughter ]

00:03:57.150 --> 00:04:00.110 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Do you often do daytime concerts?

00:04:00.110 --> 00:04:04.030
&gt;&gt; Yeah. When we can
wake up in time.

00:04:04.030 --> 00:04:06.040
[ Laughter ]

00:04:06.040 --> 00:04:07.370
&gt;&gt; Yeah, what do you
mean by daytime?

00:04:07.370 --> 00:04:09.640
&gt;&gt; Well, it was a noontime concert.

00:04:09.640 --> 00:04:10.940
&gt;&gt; In the crack of noon we play.

00:04:10.940 --> 00:04:12.240
Man.

00:04:12.240 --> 00:04:13.540
[ Laughter ]

